In[]:
def FT(im):
    # https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.fft.fft2.html
    return fft.fftshift(fft.fft2(im))  # perform also the shift to have lower frequencies at the center


def IFT(ft):
    return fft.ifft2(fft.ifftshift(ft))  # assumes ft is shifted and therefore reverses the shift before IFT

Exercise 2

We first define our filters and use filterFrequency method to compute the fourier trnasform and apply the filter. The filterFrequency method is modified to also output the FT of the image.

In[]:
def avgFilter(filterSize):
    mask = np.ones((filterSize, filterSize))
    return mask/np.sum(mask)

def averageFilterSpace(im, filterSize):
    return ndimage.convolve(im, avgFilter(filterSize))

def gaussianFilter(sigma=5):
    gv1d = signal.windows.gaussian(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, sigma).reshape(2 * round(4.0 * sigma) + 1, 1)
    gv2d = gv1d * gv1d.T
    return np.divide(gv2d, np.sum(gv2d))

def gaussianFilterSpace(im, sigma=5):
    return ndimage.convolve(im, gaussianFilter(sigma))

def filterFrequency(im, filter, *args):
    filterMask = filter(args[0])  # the usually small mask
    filterBig = np.zeros_like(im, dtype=float)  # as large as the image (dtype is important here!)
    w, h = filterMask.shape     ## First, get sizes
    w2, h2 = w / 2, h / 2  # half width and height of the "small" mask
    W, H = filterBig.shape
    W2, H2 = W / 2, H / 2  # half width and height of the "big" mask
    filterBig[int(W2 - w2):int(W2 + w2), int(H2 - h2):int(H2 + h2)] = filterMask     ## Then, paste the small mask at the center using the sizes computed before as an aid
    filterBig = fft.ifftshift(filterBig)  # FFT of the big filter: shift origin at upper-left corner
    return FT(filterBig), FT(im), np.real(IFT(FT(im) * FT(filterBig)))  # both '*' and multiply() perform elementwise product

After applying the gaussian filter you can see there is no difference between the two approaches. Even the RMS is really low. The convolution theorem works!

Now we want to see the fourier transforms of the image, the filter and the product of the image and filter. First we have to calculate the log magnitude (log to avoid big differences in values as seen in the boxplot of the exercise 1) and the phase of each fourier transform and of the product. As you can see the log magnitude of the product is eassily seen as a sum beacuse of the logarithmic properties.

In[]:
magnitude_or = np.log(np.absolute(im2_ft))
phase_or = np.angle(im2_ft)
magnitude_filter = np.log(np.absolute(filter_ft))
phase_filter = np.angle(filter_ft)
magnitude_prod = np.log(np.absolute(filter_ft*im2_ft))
phase_prod = np.angle(filter_ft*im2_ft)
vpu.showInGrid([magnitude_or, phase_or, magnitude_filter, phase_filter, magnitude_prod, phase_prod], figure_size=(10,10), m=3,n=2, subtitles=["Image log Magnitude", "Image phase", "Filter log magnitude", "Filter phase", 
                                                                                                                             "Image $\\times$ Filter magnitude", "Image $\\times$ Filter phase"])

The same can be seen with the average filter. As you can see both filters try to give more relevance to coarser details, so the finer details of the image will be erased (it will be blurred). Bigger sigmas and bigger means make the white regions of the filter to reduce in size, so less finer details will be seen and the image will be more blurred.

Exercise 3

I plotted both the time vs the mask size and the time vs the image size. In both you can see the influence of the image size and the mask size on the time it takes to compute the filtered image in the spatial and frequency domains. It is obvious that the frequency domain is faster and almost constant compared to the spatial domain.

In[]:
file = './imgs-P3/lena255.pgm'
im = np.array(Image.open(file).convert('L'))
filterSizes = np.linspace(0,25,50)
imageSizes = [64, 96, 128, 160, 192, 224, 255]
time_normal = []
time_ft = []
for f in filterSizes:
    start = timer()
    im2 = filterFrequency(im, gaussianFilter, f)
    end = timer()
    time_ft.append(end - start)
    start = timer()
    im3 = gaussianFilterSpace(im, f)
    end = timer()
    time_normal.append(end - start)
plt.plot(filterSizes, time_normal, label="Spatial")
plt.plot(filterSizes, time_ft, label="FFT")
plt.suptitle("Spatial vs FFT")
plt.title("(fixed image size of $255\\times255$)")
plt.xlabel("Filter size ($\\sigma$)")
plt.ylabel("Time (s)")
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
plt.show()

def my_mask(n):
    return np.ones((n,n)) - np.triu(np.full((n,n),2)) + np.identity(n) # np.meshgrid

def my_mask_space(im, n):
    return ndimage.convolve(im, my_mask(n), 'float64', origin= 1 if n%2!=0 else 0)

filter_ft, im2_ft, im2 = filterFrequency(im, my_mask, 20)

im3 = my_mask_space(im, 20)

Exercise 5

I enjoyed this exercise. It is one of the properties of the Fourier Transform, the linearity. This means that if you do a linear combination of an image in the frequency space you are doing the linear combination of both images. There are many others that would also be interesting to see.

F1 = FT(stp1)
F2 = FT(stp2)

inv_comb = np.absolute(IFT(comb))

Exercise 7

It is the same code of the band pass filter but adding some smothing to the mask. If the filter elements are far away from the ones that are going to be set to 1, we set them to 0. And as they move closer to the elements set to 1 their values becomes closer to 1. The level of smoothenes could even be controled by modifying the exponent of the equation.

In[]:
def bandPassFilter(shape, r=None, R=None):
    n, m = shape
    m2, n2 = np.floor(m / 2.0), np.floor(n / 2.0)
    [vx, vy] = np.meshgrid(np.arange(-m2, m2 + 1), np.arange(-n2, n2 + 1))
    distToCenter = np.sqrt(vx ** 2.0 + vy ** 2.0)
    max = np.max(distToCenter)
    filter = np.zeros(distToCenter.shape)
    if R is None:  # low-pass filter assumed
        assert r is not None, "at least one size for filter is expected"
        filter[distToCenter<r] = 1
        filter[distToCenter>=r] = (-(distToCenter[distToCenter>=r]-max)/(max-r))**2 # same as np.less(distToCenter, r)
    elif r is None:  # high-pass filter assumed
        filter[distToCenter>R]=1 # same as np.greater(distToCenter, R)
        filter[distToCenter<=R] = (distToCenter[distToCenter<=R]/R)**2
    else:  # both, R and r given, then band-pass filter
        if r > R:
            r, R = R, r  # swap to ensure r < R (alternatively, warn the user, or throw an exception)
        filter[np.logical_and(distToCenter<R, distToCenter>r)] = 1
        filter[distToCenter<=r] = (distToCenter[distToCenter<=r]/r)**2
        filter[distToCenter>=R] = (-(distToCenter[distToCenter>=R]-max)/(max-R))**2
        
    bDisplay = True
    if bDisplay:
        plt.imshow(filter, cmap='gray')
        plt.title("The filter in the frequency domain")
        plt.show()
        # Image.fromarray((255*filter).astype(np.uint8)).save('filter.png')

    return filter
